		/// <para><see href="https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/winbase/nf-winbase-mapviewoffileexnuma#parameters">Read more on learn.microsoft.com</see>.</para>
		/// </param>
		/// <param name="lpBaseAddress">
		/// <para>A pointer to the memory address in the calling process address space where mapping begins. This must be a multiple of the system's memory allocation granularity, or the function fails. To determine the memory allocation granularity of the system, use the <a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/windows/desktop/api/sysinfoapi/nf-sysinfoapi-getsysteminfo">GetSystemInfo</a> function. If there is not enough address space at the specified address, the function fails. If the <i>lpBaseAddress</i> parameter is <b>NULL</b>, the operating system chooses the mapping address. While it is possible to specify an address that is safe now (not used by the operating system), there is no guarantee that the address will remain safe over time. Therefore, it is better to let the operating system choose the address. In this case, you would not store pointers in the memory mapped file; you would store offsets from the base of the file mapping so that the mapping can be used at any address.</para>
