/c> must not be a pointer or use <c>StringCchCopy(buffer, ARRAYSIZE(buffer), src);</c>, being aware that, when copying to a pointer, the caller is responsible for passing in the size of the pointed-to memory in characters. Review <a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/windows/desktop/AppUIStart/sec-ui">Security Considerations: Windows User Interface</a> before continuing.</para>
